intro: Acer negundo f. bicolor, commonly known as the twinleaf maple, is a deciduous tree characterized by its distinctive foliage. Its leaves are palmately lobed, with two prominent lobes on each side, giving it a unique appearance. The plant is native to North America and thrives in moist, well-drained soils. It produces small, yellowish-green flowers in early spring, followed by winged samaras in the fall. The tree is often used in ornamental landscaping due to its attractive form and seasonal color changes.
